<task id="023" project="spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r3">
  <metadata>
    <title>Make SprkChatInput editable on first load (FR-06)</title>
    <phase>Phase B — Assistant pane</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-hours>2</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>010</dependencies>
    <blocks>025</blocks>
    <tags>react, frontend, shared-components</tags>
    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Modifies SprkChat.tsx — a shared component in `@spaarke/ui-components` consumed beyond SpaarkeAi. Changes a behavioral invariant (input enabled vs disabled). FULL rigor with code-review + adr-check gates.</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>B</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Make `SprkChatInput` editable on first load before a chat session exists. The current
    disabled condition `disabled={isStreaming || !session || isSessionLoading}` blocks
    users from typing until a session is created. Per FR-06, the user should be able to
    type immediately on cold load; the session is created lazily on first send via the
    existing `useChatSession.createSession()` flow. Drop the `!session` and
    `isSessionLoading` guards from the disabled condition — keep only `isStreaming`.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    React 19 + Fluent v9 developer comfortable working in the `@spaarke/ui-components`
    shared library, with awareness that `SprkChat` is consumed by multiple solutions
    (SpaarkeAi and any other host).
  </role>

  <goal>
    `SprkChat.tsx`'s input is editable on cold load (no session yet). Disabled-state
    condition is `disabled={isStreaming}` only. First send triggers lazy session creation
    via the existing `useChatSession` hook, then sends the user's message in the
    newly-created session. No regression in active-streaming UX (still disabled during
    streaming).
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      FR-06 unblocks the welcome-state UX: users can type into the input on cold load
      without waiting for a backend session to be created. The `useChatSession` hook
      already supports lazy creation (verified during spec phase). This is a tiny code
      change but high-leverage — combined with the chrome trim (task 020), it makes the
      welcome state feel responsive and minimal. Task 025 (toolbar restructure) also
      modifies this file; this task must complete first.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.UI.Components/src/components/SprkChat/SprkChat.tsx</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-012">SprkChat lives in `@spaarke/ui-components` — modifications here affect all consumers. Validate that no consumer relies on the old disabled-on-no-session behavior (grep for `SprkChat` usages outside SpaarkeAi).</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-021">No styling changes; existing tokens preserved. Disabled visual state of the input is governed by Fluent v9 `Input` primitives — no manual color overrides.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-022">React 19. Hooks-only — no class components, no legacy lifecycle methods.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-028">No auth changes. `useChatSession.createSession()` already uses `authenticatedFetch`. Do not introduce any `accessToken` props.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">FR-06 acceptance: user can type into input on cold load; first send creates session via BFF. Streaming-disable invariant preserved.</constraint>
    <constraint source="project">This task touches ONLY `SprkChat.tsx`. Task 025 (toolbar) is the next file editor — coordinate to avoid stomping on each other's diffs.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-012-shared-components.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-021-fluent-design-system.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-022-pcf-platform-libraries.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-028-spaarke-auth-architecture.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r3/CLAUDE.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r3/spec.md</file>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r3/plan.md</file>
